"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from the Relatives &amp; Residents Association (ACQ 11)&#xa0;\nAbout R&amp;RA\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nEvidence&#xa0;\n* CQC is not acting as an agent for improvement as required in their governing legislation;\n* CQC does not have sufficient expertise in the care home sector;\n* CQC’s strategy should build in the capability to inspect care homes at least twice a year;\n* performance measures for care homes should focus on improvement in the health, safety and well-being of residents;\n* there should be two inspections of care homes per year;\n* a focus on a few selected standards only is negligent;\n* specialists with expertise in care homes should be recruited to inspect care homes;\n* CQC appears to be taking steps to being a learning organisation, but they have a long way to go;\n* CQC could reduce the burdens on care homes for older people by becoming a reliable and trusted organisation;\n* CQC should carry out an evaluation of its priorities and inspection methodology;\n* CQCs regulatory regime should be specifically tailored to meet the needs of each sector;\n* the DH should improve its capability and expertise on the regulation of safety and quality; and\n* the CQC website should not allow care homes to expunge their (often poor) records by changing the name under which the provider is registered.\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \ninspections remain\n \ntoo infrequent;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nCQC’s inspection methodology remains inadequate;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nenforcement action is lacking;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \ninspectors of care homes often\n \nlack expertise in the care home sector, in particular in care for older people;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \ninspection reports lack sufficient information for the public to judge how a home is performing and for prospective residents and their families to choose a home that will meet their needs.\n&#xa0;\nFrequency of inspections&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nInspection methodology&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nEnforcement Action&#xa0;\nInspectors lacking expertise&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nLack of information in inspection reports&#xa0;\n1. How much time was spent in the home? \n2. How many inspectors? \n3. The name of the inspector \n4. The time of the inspection \n5. How many relatives were spoken with or involved in the inspection via a survey? \n6. Whether there is a registered manager in post? \n7. If so, the name and qualifications of the manager \n8. If none, to say so and give the reasons \n9. Plus provider’s plan to deal with the vacancy and appoint a new manager \n10. Which regulations were found to have been breached during the inspection? \n11. The specific powers being used to take enforcement action \n12. Plus the time-table for this \n13. Which regulations are still in breach from any previous inspections and reasons, if any, for any continued breach \n14. If so, what further enforcement action will be taken? \n15. The number of complaints received, what they were about and whether or not they have been resolved? \n16. Any safeguarding concerns and if so, what about? and to whom referred? \n17. Some detail about the staffing ratio in the home and \n18. Whether there are any stimulating activities\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;October 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n 18 April 2013 PQ WA total number of warning notices issued by CQC in 2012/13 was 1178 for all regulated services, approx. 35000 c3.5% of the total.\n"